{{context|date=April 2018}}
'''Wireless Communications Service (WCS)''' is a set of frequency bands designated in the [[United States]] in the 2305–2320 and 2345–2360 [[Megahertz|MHz]] spectrum range. The most common use of WCS spectrum is [[mobile phone|mobile voice]] and [[mobile data|data]] services, including [[cell phone]], [[text messaging]], and [[Internet]].<ref name=fcc>{{cite web |url=https://www.fcc.gov/wireless/bureau-divisions/broadband-division/wireless-communications-service-wcs |title=Wireless Communications Service (WCS) |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |date=2017-03-08 |accessdate=2018-04-08}}</ref>
There are four blocks in WCS:<ref name=fcc/> * A Block (2305–2310 and 2350–2355&nbsp;MHz) * B Block (2310–2315 and 2355–2360&nbsp;MHz) * C Block (2315–2320&nbsp;MHz) * D Block (2345–2350&nbsp;MHz)
